<paragraph id="8BB9368B197CFFBB6A8BA1B973D4FD11" blockId="92.[189,1399,478,645]" pageId="92" pageNumber="93">
<taxonomicName id="4C064D08197CFFBB6A8BA1B97266FE6C" authorityName="Thompson" authorityYear="1966" box="[189,586,478,504]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Sphegina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="92" pageNumber="93" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hansoni" subGenus="Asiosphegina">
<emphasis id="B972EA99197CFFBB6A8BA1B97266FE6C" box="[189,586,478,504]" italics="true" pageId="92" pageNumber="93">Sphegina (Asiosphegina) hansoni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
resembles other 
<taxonomicName id="4C064D08197CFFBB6923A1B973AEFE6C" authorityName="Meigen" authorityYear="1822" box="[789,898,478,504]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Sphegina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="92" pageNumber="93" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B972EA99197CFFBB6923A1B973AEFE6C" box="[789,898,478,504]" italics="true" pageId="92" pageNumber="93">Sphegina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with strongly asymmetrical male sternum IV posteriorly armed with strong black setae, but is easily distinguished by the characters given in the key. The carinate metatrochanter is a more unique character which it shares only with 
<taxonomicName id="4C064D08197CFFBB6F3FA24271F7FDF6" authorityName="Hippa, van Steenis &amp; Mutin" authorityYear="2015" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Sphegina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="92" pageNumber="93" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="carinata" subGenus="Asiosphegina">
<emphasis id="B972EA99197CFFBB6F3FA24271F7FDF6" italics="true" pageId="92" pageNumber="93">Sphegina (Asiosphegina) carinata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="4C064D08197CFFBB6BDAA22E7288FDF6" authorityName="Hippa, van Steenis &amp; Mutin" authorityYear="2015" box="[492,676,584,611]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Sphegina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="92" pageNumber="93" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="malaisei" subGenus="Asiosphegina">
<emphasis id="B972EA99197CFFBB6BDAA22E7288FDF6" box="[492,676,584,611]" italics="true" pageId="92" pageNumber="93">S. (A.) malaisei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C064D08197CFFBB68D4A22E73A9FDF6" authority="Steenis &amp; Hippa &amp; Mutin, 2018" authorityName="Steenis &amp; Hippa &amp; Mutin" authorityYear="2018" box="[738,901,584,611]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Sphegina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="92" pageNumber="93" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ornata" status="sp. nov." subGenus="Asiosphegina">
<emphasis id="B972EA99197CFFBB68D4A22E73A9FDF6" box="[738,901,584,611]" italics="true" pageId="92" pageNumber="93">S. (A.) ornata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A24157E2197CFFBB69B9A22F73C7FDF6" box="[911,1003,584,610]" pageId="92" pageNumber="93" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
In the male genitalia, the almost symmetrical surstyli is a unique character within this group of species.
</paragraph>
